# Battlezone

$info=bzone,bzone2
$icon=bzone
$data
Mfg.
_Atari
-
Year
_1980
-
Format
_Vector
_Horizontal
$bio
Designed by Morgan Hoff and 
Ed Rotberg-Programmed by Ed
Rotberg and Jed Margolin


Battlezone was the first 
environmental 3D landscape
game. The game used a system
of bit-slice processors 
called a "mathbox" to do 3D 
calculations for the display.
This kind of "squeezing the 
most out of minimal hardware"
mindset was what led Atari to 
create the innovative games
it did in the 1980's. Atari
has sold approximately 75,000
units. 


Battlezone was so innovative 
for its time,  the US Army
commissioned Atari to create
a version of the game for
infantry vehicle training.  
Ed Rotberg was assigned the 
project, but was very opposed
to it. Major Dave Robinson and
General Donn Starry of the
U.S.
Army were responsible for
bringing Atari the idea of
making a military version
to be used in training.


It is questionable whether the
US Army versions were ever 
produced,  but it is rumored 
that Videotopia (the traveling
video games exhibit) has one 
in their possession.


The volcano erupting in the
background was created by
Owen Rubin (Major Havoc).
Rubin pestered Rotberg to
add the volcano, but he was
too busy to write the code,
and told Rubin that if he
wanted the erupting volcano,
he'd have to write the code.
The next morning, Rotberg
walked in to a volcano
erupting onscreen and the
code listing on his desk.


The radar and warning messages
were "colorized" by red
cellophane placed atop the
screen.


Tips and Tricks:


Killing tanks:


Enemy tanks have the same
firing limitation that you do-
the shot has to disappear out
of range or hit something
before they can fire again.
This is the key - keep them
missing you and nail them
before they can reload. Never
sit still.

You need to get the enemy tank
in front of you (obviously).
The best bet is to just back
up until the tank is in your
cone of vision. Back up
straight and listen for it to
shoot at you. When you see the
shot pass, briefly turn
towards the tank, then resume
backing up straight. Repeat
this until the tank is
visible.
It won't be able to zero in on
you if you keep moving.

If you hit a barricade while
backing up, you have to react
quickly to avoid getting shot.
Move forward, then turn
slightly and then keep backing
up. If you're near the pyramid
next to the short cube, you 
may get hung up between them.
It's a good idea to know where
they are and avoid them.

Once the tank is in front of
you, if it's not facing you,
just zero in on it and kill
it.
If it is facing you (and
coming at you) you may be able
to get a barricade in-between
it and you. If you can, it
will run into it, then turn to 
avoid it. You can then nail it
once it moves away from the
barricade.

If you can't get a shot at a
tank's side, check the next
section for tips on killing it
head-on.


Regular tanks:


Drive towards it at an angle
(never directly head-on). It
won't be able to zero in on
you. You may have to keep
adjusting your course slightly
as you go. Drive even with or
slightly past it, pause a
second, then back up, turn
towards it and fire.

What happens is: as you pass
the tank, it will turn towards
you to zero in, but you're
moving faster than it can
turn. If you do it right, as
you back up, it will fire at
you and miss, giving you
enough time to aim.


Supertanks:


Follow the same directions as
for killing regular tanks,
except don't pause when you
pull side-by-side with it -
immediately back up, turn and
kill it. You may actually hit
the tank, but that's fine. It
will shoot at you and miss,
giving you time to blow it
away. Once you master the
timing of this, tanks are a
breeze.


Missiles:


Missiles are tricky to get the
hang of. The first one comes
at you straight, so you can
just back up in a straight
line to kill it.  The second
one (or two) will straighten
out near the end of their
attack so you can do the same
to them. After that, you have
to get the hang of their
flight pattern.

As soon as you hear the
missile coming, start backing
up and turn your tank so the
missile will come down just to
the left of the center of the
screen (use the crosshairs as
a guide), then back your tank
up in a straight line. The
missile will zig-zag on the
way down, then go straight, go
slightly left, then turn
sharply right. Watch for that
straight part of its flight,
wait for the left turn, then
when it turns to the right -
fire. The missile will fly
right into your shot. If you
position your tank correctly
when the missile comes down,
you don't need to do any more
turning.

If you miss, you may be able
to dodge the missile by moving
ahead and to the right, or if
you started backing up soon
enough, you may get off a
second shot (it will repeat
the straight, left, right
pattern if given enough room,
allowing you to shoot using
the same method).

This takes a bit of practice,
but once you get into the
rhythm, you can kill off
missiles to your heart's
content.


Saucers:


Don't go after saucers unless 
you know exactly where the 
enemy tank is, and can do so 
safely. If the enemy tank gets
in directly behind you, then 
don't chase a saucer down - 
the tank will shoot you in the
back. During a missile attack,
concentrate on the missiles - 
don't worry about the saucer 
until you're back to fighting 
tanks.

You can lurk (or hunt) for 
saucers, (sort of like in 
Asteroids). You need to get 
behind a tall barricade (the 
one shaped like a refrigerator 
works best). When a missile 
attacks, get right up to the 
barricade - then the saucer 
will jump over the barricade 
and you. As soon as it's 
overhead, spin the tank in 
place to the right. If you 
time it right, the missile 
won't be able to exit the 
radar screen and will be stuck
behind you as long as you're
spinning. Now you just keep
spinning until a saucer 
happens by. If you stop to 
shoot it, the missile will
escape, so try to shoot it on
the fly. Eventually the 
missile will escape on its own
although you can delay it by
backing up while spinning to
keep it in range.


Miscellaneous:


Free tanks are awarded at 
15,000 and 100,000, missiles
arrive around 15,000 and
Supertanks show up after 
20,000 (not including points 
earned from saucers). This 
changes depending on how a 
machine is set up. 
Battlezone's score probably 
wraps over at 10,000,000. Some 
time after 600,000 the 
Supertanks are replaced by the 
slower (lower scoring) regular 
tanks. This is a plus though, 
since it's safer to go after 
saucers.

Between attacks, drive forward
into an open area, so you have
a clear space to back into
during the next attack. During
missile attacks, you'll 
usually have to turn to the 
right to position the missile 
correctly.

Keep an eye on the radar 
screen when a new tank attacks
especially later in the 
Supertank rounds. If it puts 
one directly behind you, you 
have very little time to get 
away. Turn while driving away 
from it fast. Once you get 
clear, then you can back up 
and get it in front of you.

Practice shooting while 
turning. You can either 
practice on tanks (risky) or 
on barricades between attacks.

$end


