Having a googolplex of
possible combinations, there
was no singular pattern to
the game, and players lost
interest.


Some tips from "Alienation":


Where we've played it was 
very popular because we found
a way to play it forever and 
with nice hi-scores, as 
follows:


1. first, go up and make 3 
rectangular "doors" at the top 
where the "spiders" appears,
more or less - like this:


------------------------------
|  |  |________________|  |  |
|  |______________________|  |
|____________________________|


This will make new spiders to 
loop in this doors forever.


2. Then isolate the "qix" in 
half a screen (up or down) by 
dividing the screen.


----------------
|              |
|   *-> quix   |
|_____________ |
|              |
|              |
|______________|


3. then make on the other side 
little constructions like this:


 _
| |
|_|_
  | |
  | |
  |_|_
    | |
    |_|


At the points common to each 
block you can then pass 
directly to he other side, 
while the spiders have to go 
around. The blocks can be 
shaped and tall as the player 
whiches, but keep them thin.

If you keep doing this, after 
a while the level will end 
closing with 99% !!!!!!!!!!! 
And with the color you were 
using to make the last
block. (it seems the qix is 
closed in the block you just 
made).

This is probably a bug in the 
program...

Some times it takes a long 
time to close but this works 
almost every time.

or, as the spiders never come 
out, (apart from the first 
two) you can just keep playing 
and (as I did often) just make 
some drawings!!!

After some levels, the qix 
get's very fast and nasty, so 
it becomes very difficult to 
repeat this procedure forever. 

$end

