$data
$bio
Tips and Tricks:


This game has hidden coins
that appear when you jump in
certain spots. The demo screen
shows a couple of these. Some
of
them will give you 60 gold or
more every time.


On the screen after you kill
the vampire and get the broad
sword, there are some
platforms that contain a shoe
shop and a
cure shop. There are stairs
leading down to the cure shop,
and there's a little
mushroom-type guy. Wait for
him to go down the
stairs, and then stand so that
you're almost off the topmost
stair. He'll come back up and
hit you, making you fall off
the stairs.
Hold the joystick to the left
so that when you land you walk
into the bottom step. This
will drop a 60+ coin.


On the stage just after you
kill the red knight, you'll
see some little jellyfish-type
things on platforms over the
water. At the first
jellyfish you come to, wait
for him to drop into the
water, and then stand at the
very edge of the platform
(halfway off) and let
him hit you. You'll take a
small amount of damage, but
you'll get a large amount of
cash.


Jump for coins all over the
place - you never know what
you'll find!

$end

#-----------------------------
#WWF Superstars
$info=
$bio
Tips and Tricks:


An excellent WWF Superstars
strategy guide by Andre
Vieira:


Character Selection- most
people like to select Randy
Savage and the Big Boss Man
(size and speed). My
preference leaned
more towards Hulk Hogan and
Randy Savage. The good
characters to me were Jim
Duggan, the Boss Man, Savage
and Hogan
because of their special moves
and high kicks. 


A good tip/strategy when
starting is to rush the
opposing tag team with a
flying kick to knock them BOTH
down. If this was timed
right, especially on the
earlier levels, you could wear
down both players before the
first computer opponent could
wrestle you
one-on-one. Here's how it
works. The ring announcer is
introducing the wrestlers.
Your wrestler closest to the
center of the ring
(lower wrestler) charges their
lower wrestler, knocking him
down. The computer's upper
wrestler that starts the match
will come
down beside him, also getting
knocked down in the process.
You go after the opponent who
is NOT the legal man in the
ring,
and throw him into the other
wrestler. If all goes well,
you can knock down each
opponent in turn, or both
simultaneously until
you get knocked down or the
third man in the ring leaves.


My pattern for victory would
be to grab my opponent,
bodyslam him, pick him up,
throw him to the ropes and
clothesline him.
He will get up, but be out of
breath. At that point, I would
get behind him and deliver a
suplex/atomic drop. Wait until
he is out
of breath and give another
suplex/atomic drop, then when
he gets up a third time,
clothesline him. He will then
try to tag his
partner, but I try to
intercept him and throw him
towards my side of the ring
and give him a flying
dropkick. After that, I pin
him
and let my partner deal with
his partner.


You should always try to pin
the computer opponent near
your side of the ring so that
when his partner rushes to
help, you can
flip him out of the ring using
your partner. It also cuts
down the computer's chances of
breaking up the pin. A neat
bug that
happened VERY rarely was to
have both computer opponents
down on health after beating
them silly (using the opening
trick
outlined above) then throwing
the legal man out of the ring.
If the computer has been
pounded sufficiently, you can
pin the
computer's partner while the
legal man lies motionless
outside the ring. You won't
get the three count for the
pin, but your
partner will enter the ring
and you can start him running
until he is halfway across and
make him jump into a flying
bodyslam
onto the prone opponent
outside the ring. The clock
goes until 20, at which point
the computer is counted out.
That gives your
second guy time for one or two
more bodyslams since after he
lands the first one, he
automatically travels back to
his corner.


If both your players are
running low on health, a good
strategy is to leave the ring,
hoping to lure the computer
opponent
outside. That way, you have a
chance to knock his energy
down a bit and possibly count
him out of the ring. If he
does not
come out for you, move towards
your side of the ring near the
turnbuckle. The computer will
follow you there, and if you
move
a bit towards the right a bit,
the computer will be close to
the ropes but facing you
still. Eventually your partner
will come down
and grab him while he is still
facing you. You can come back
into the ring and beat him up
a bit, giving you time to tag
up or
exit the ring to lure him
again.


In the championship match
against Andre the Giant and
Ted Dibiasi, I like to use the
rushing tactic outlined above.
If the Giant
is slated to start the match,
you may have time to throw
Dibiasi out of the ring, and
throw the Giant into the ropes
for an
eventual back drop or drop
kick. If Dibiasi starts the
match, you may have the chance
to knock down Dibiasi, whip
Andre into
the ropes, pick up Dibiasi and
throw him into Andre's path,
concluding with giving Andre a
drop kick. At that point, the
computer
opponents are ready to kill
you so exiting the ring is a
good idea. To beat them, I
like to concentrate on Andre.
The sequence is
fairly simple. First, wait
until Andre comes close to you
and tries to slap you down. If
you avoid his attack, you can
immediately
grab him, and whip him into
the ropes (Button B) at which
point you can either give him
a sunset flip or a flying
dropkick. When
he is down, you can pick him
up and repeat as necessary.
Just remember not to grab him
until he tries to swat you. If
he is
sufficiently softened up, you
can pick him up and deliver a
bodyslam. You will also be
able to give him a clothesline
(or in
Randy Savage's case, a flying
clothesline). At that point,
he will try to tag in Ted
Dibiasi. For the Million
Dollar Man, I exit the
ring, using the second
strategy outlined above and
hoping that I can beat him up
sufficiently for either the
count-out or for him
to tag Andre back in. Since
the time runs fairly quickly
in these matches, I go for the
count-out although technically
the
championship does not change
hands on a disqualification.
But then again, it's only a
video game as opposed to
"professional
wrestling" 


When you are playing two
players against the computer,
there are many ways to be
wrestling without having to be
the legal
man in the ring. This is
especially useful if both you
and your partner are low on
health. At the beginning of
any match which
your partner starts (this
alternates every match), he
just has to kick you once
before you reach your corner
and VOILA! instant
double-team action! Of course
your moves are limited to
punches, kicks, body slams and
sunset flips. With another
player who
knows this secret, the game
becomes a laugh riot! You
could theoretically keep both
players in the ring for most
of the match.
Another thing to do is when
your partner and his computer
opponent exit the ring, try to
enter the ring before the
computer
opponent does. His partner
will not come after you, and
if your partner does not come
in, you can throw the computer
guy out
of the ring or lay down an
extra-rich layer of whoopass
on him while your partner
waits. Just remember to keep
moving or you
will automatically go back to
your corner. I remember when I
used to go to the billiards
hall where this game was and I
would
play with this other guy who
was even better than I was. We
would have the strategies down
to a science as we mow down
opponents left and right. He
would kick me to stay in the
ring, then I would grab the
computer opponent and throw
him towards
my partner, who would flip him
out of the ring. I would run
and jump out of the ring,
landing on him and my partner
would do
the same immediately after me.
The computer's partner would
come over and I would rush
back into the ring, waiting
for the
computer. If he came back in,
I would throw him back out and
splash him outside the ring
again. If we were low on
energy
(indicated by the music
change) we would lure the
computer outside and go for
the count-out.


There are some final pointers
in playing WWF Superstars,
such as keeping track of how
much space you have between
your
player and the ropes, lest you
try a suplex too close to the
ropes. That also relates to
moves off the top rope, making
sure your
opponent is not too close to
the ropes or too far away.
Doing a drop kick off the top
turnbuckle makes you face
different
directions depending on which
turnbuckle you launch from. 

$end


