#Xevious
$info=xevious,xeviousa,sxeviuo
s,xevios
$icon=xevious
$data
Mfg.
_Namco
_(Atari License)
-
Year
_1982
-
Format
_Raster
_Vertical
$bio
At the beginning of the game
go to the bottom right of the
screen and keep the BOMB
button pressed.

In the original the message
is:
Namco original
program by Evezoo

but in the bootleg, it is:
Dead copy making
copy under Namco program

And in Super Xevious it is:
Special thanks for you
by game designer Evezoo


Xevious was among the first
games to use pre-rendered
graphics.


Tips and Tricks:


Keep firing! At the very
least, keep your finger held
on your fire button and you
will send off a steady stream
of slow
shots, even with no air
attacks present. This is a
useful guide as to whether or
not you can fit between the
tumbling walls,
and if you're concentrating on
bombing, the glassy sound of
you actually hitting an
air-based enemy will alert you
that
another air attack has
arrived.


Watch the edges of your
bomb-sight (the floating
cross-hairs) closely - they
always blink red when you're
over a target.
Two targets located next to
each other can be destroyed
with one shot placed firmly
between them, as can a
grouping of
four ground targets - very
useful for getting rid of
those clumps of shot- spewing
hexes (actually octagons!) in
the later
stages.


There are many hidden rocket
silos, which need to be bombed
in order for the rockets to
show themselves. Once the
rockets appear, they can be
bombed again for extra points.
Although there doesn't appear
to be any reasoning behind
their location, they are
nonetheless always located in
the same place, and your bomb-
sight will always alert you
when
you move over one. To find
them, sweep over seemingly
innocuous areas of green
field, sandy desert and strips
of grey -
your sights should soon pick
them out.


The first one is quite early
on (about 30 seconds into the
game or so), in the right-hand
corner of a field before you
move
over trees and into the first
lot of ground-based targets.
Another can be found just
after a horizontal road that
runs the
whole length of the screen,
dead center in the green
strip. Also check to the right
of the moving target on the
pier after
flying over the ocean for the
first time.


A definite one is after the
first set of tumbling walls,
above and to the left of the
large grey pyramid. 1 can be
found in the
run-up to the first mother
ship - when tackling the
ground targets, look where the
two vertical roads are joined
by a
thinner horizontal strip - one
is hidden in the top-left
crook. Four are located in a
diagonal line before the
second mother
ship, and after you pass over
the bird in the desert the
second time there are 8 in two
long rows of 4!!


There are several "Special"
flags that give you an extra
ship. The Specials are not
detected by your sights - but
if you
imagine them to be submarines
moving at slow speed through
horizontal strips of water,
you're sure to find several.

The first Special is in the
first cross screen river after
three tanks that don't move.
It's usually in the lower part
of the river
on the far left or far right.
Its position moves around so
you need to bomb the whole
river.

During the first set of
tumbling walls, you'll pass
over a half-desert,
half-forest area. Look for a
small lake shaped like a
kidney with a thin stream
running to the right - bomb in
a straight line across the
stream repeatedly (including
into the
lake) and you'll find one
Special. Pick it up for a
bonus ship.

When the gray "walls" start
spinning toward you, wait
until you see the large gray
house in the mid-left part of
the screen.
Immediately fly to the
left-most part of the screen
and wait for your bomb sight
to start blinking, then bomb
away! A tower
will grow from the sand. Bomb
it, and you get a free ship.


Hint on second mothership:
Just before the escort you are
swarmed by ships and 1
anti-aircraft gun, there are 4
missile
silos in a small clearing.
They are laid out in a
diagonal going up from left to
right. If you leave them alone
you will have
an easier time getting to the
second mothership.

Hit the second mothership as
it is coming down!! Don't let
it start moving with you!!


An interesting story by
Dungeon Dave:


One memorable game I played
(on the arcade machine, with
only 3 lives to start with!)
was when I achieved a score of
more than 400,000 - but
although this was a long game,
it was no longer to some
others I had played around the
same
time but with scores in the
200,000 mark. Quite late into
the game, I was faced with
four clumps of 4 shot-spewers
on
either side of the screen, and
after bombing the first clump
with one shot I was rewarded
with the victory tunes of an
extra life. Bombing the clump
on the other side also rang
the same tunes, and the same
thing happened with the other
two clumps - I had suddenly
gained 4 extra lives and my
score had jumped from 150K to
post-400K. To this day, I
still
believe it to be a bug.
[Anyone else see this? -Roger]

$end

